import LevyStochCalc.Basic

/-!
# Layer 0 substrate: Poisson random measure on `[0, ‚ąě) √ó E`

A *Poisson random measure* on the time-space `[0, ‚ąě) √ó E` (where `E` is a
measurable mark space with ŌÉ-finite intensity `őĹ`), defined over a
probability space `(ő©, P)`, is a measurable family

  `N : ő© ‚Üí Measure (‚ĄĚ √ó E)`

with the following properties:

* For each measurable `B ‚äÜ ‚ĄĚ √ó E` with `(volume.restrict [0,‚ąě) ‚äó őĹ)(B) < ‚ąě`,
  `N(¬∑, B) ~ Poisson` with mean equal to that intensity.
* For any pairwise-disjoint family of such sets, the random variables
  `(N(¬∑, B_i))_i` are independent under `P`.

This is the time-aware structure required for the *compensated* integral
`‚ąę_0^t ‚ąę_E ŌÜ(s, e) √Ď(ds, de)` to be well-defined.

## References

* Applebaum, *L√©vy Processes and Stochastic Calculus*, Cambridge 2009, ¬ß2.3, Thm 2.3.1.
* Ikeda‚ÄďWatanabe, *Stochastic Differential Equations and Diffusion Processes*,
  North-Holland 1989, ¬ßI.8.
* Sato, *L√©vy Processes and Infinitely Divisible Distributions*,
  Cambridge 1999, ¬ß19.

## Status

Phase 2 spec: structure fields wired to real Mathlib types on the `‚ĄĚ √ó E`
time-space. The intensity is `volume.restrict (Set.Ici 0) ‚äó őĹ` (Lebesgue
restricted to `[0, ‚ąě)` tensor `őĹ` on the mark space).

Existence theorem `PoissonRandomMeasure.exists_of_sigmaFinite` carries the
substantive `sorry` (Ionescu-Tulcea construction).
-/

open MeasureTheory ProbabilityTheory
open scoped NNReal ENNReal

namespace LevyStochCalc.Poisson

universe u v

variable {ő© : Type u} [MeasurableSpace ő©]
variable {E : Type v} [MeasurableSpace E]

/-- The Poisson distribution `Poisson(őľ)` viewed as a measure on `‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě` (via
the natural inclusion `‚Ąē ‚Ü™ ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě`). Convenience for stating
`P.map (N ¬∑ A) = ‚Ä¶` since `N(¬∑, A) : ő© ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě` (an extended-real count). -/
noncomputable def poissonMeasureENN (őľ : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0) : Measure ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě :=
  (ProbabilityTheory.poissonMeasure őľ).map (fun n : ‚Ąē => (n : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě))

/-- The reference intensity on `‚ĄĚ √ó E`: Lebesgue on `[0, ‚ąě)` tensor `őĹ` on
the mark space. -/
noncomputable def referenceIntensity {E : Type v} [MeasurableSpace E]
    (őĹ : Measure E) : Measure (‚ĄĚ √ó E) :=
  (volume.restrict (Set.Ici (0 : ‚ĄĚ))).prod őĹ

/-- A *Poisson random measure on `[0, ‚ąě) √ó E`* with intensity
`volume.restrict [0,‚ąě) ‚äó őĹ`, defined over a probability space `(ő©, P)`.

The Applebaum (2009) Definition 2.3.1 properties are: (a) `N(¬∑, A)` is
Poisson-distributed (captured by `poisson_law`); (b) disjoint-family values
are independent (captured by `independent_disjoint`); (c) `N` is an
integer-valued atomic measure (encoded by `integer_valued` below ‚ÄĒ which
follows from (a) since Poisson distributions are supported on `‚Ąē`, but is
made explicit here as an a.s. claim because Mathlib's `Measure` type
allows non-integer values in general). -/
structure PoissonRandomMeasure
    (P : Measure ő©) [IsProbabilityMeasure P]
    (őĹ : Measure E) [SigmaFinite őĹ] where
  /-- The underlying ŌČ-indexed family of measures on `‚ĄĚ √ó E`. -/
  N : ő© ‚Üí Measure (‚ĄĚ √ó E)
  /-- For each measurable `B ‚äÜ ‚ĄĚ √ó E`, the map `ŌČ ‚Ü¶ N(ŌČ, B)` is measurable. -/
  measurable_eval : ‚ąÄ {B : Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E)}, MeasurableSet B ‚Üí
    Measurable (fun ŌČ => N ŌČ B)
  /-- **Applebaum 2.3.1(c).** For measurable `B` with finite intensity,
  `N(¬∑, B)` is a.s. `‚Ąē`-valued (in the natural embedding `‚Ąē ‚Ü™ ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě`).
  Follows from `poisson_law` since the Poisson distribution is supported
  on `‚Ąē`, but is exposed as a structural field so downstream code can use
  it without having to re-derive it through the Poisson-law characterisation
  each time (L10 fix 2026-05-22 per red-team P04). -/
  integer_valued : ‚ąÄ {B : Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E)}, MeasurableSet B ‚Üí
    referenceIntensity őĹ B ‚Č† ‚ä§ ‚Üí
    ‚ąÄŠĶź ŌČ ‚ąāP, ‚ąÉ n : ‚Ąē, N ŌČ B = n
  /-- `N(¬∑, B)` has `Poisson` law with mean `(referenceIntensity őĹ)(B)` under
  `P`, for every measurable `B` with finite intensity. -/
  poisson_law : ‚ąÄ {B : Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E)}, MeasurableSet B ‚Üí
    referenceIntensity őĹ B ‚Č† ‚ä§ ‚Üí
    P.map (fun ŌČ => N ŌČ B) = poissonMeasureENN (referenceIntensity őĹ B).toNNReal
  /-- For any pairwise-disjoint countable family of measurable subsets of
  `‚ĄĚ √ó E`, the family of evaluation random variables `(ŌČ ‚Ü¶ N(ŌČ, B_i))_i` is
  independent under `P`. -/
  independent_disjoint :
    ‚ąÄ {őĻ : Type*} (B : őĻ ‚Üí Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E)),
      (‚ąÄ i, MeasurableSet (B i)) ‚Üí
      Pairwise (fun i j => Disjoint (B i) (B j)) ‚Üí
      ProbabilityTheory.iIndepFun (fun (i : őĻ) (ŌČ : ő©) => N ŌČ (B i)) P
  /-- **ŌÉ-algebra-level past/future independence.** The ŌÉ-algebra generated by
  `{N(¬∑, B) : B ‚äÜ (‚ąí‚ąě, s] √ó E, B measurable}` (the "past at time `s`") is
  independent of `ŌÉ(N(¬∑, (s, t] √ó A))` (a future increment).

  This is strictly stronger than `independent_disjoint` (which is iIndepFun
  for finite/countable families) and is needed to apply
  `MeasureTheory.condExp_indep_eq` in the compensated stochastic-integral
  proofs. For PRMs it follows from joint independence on disjoint subsets;
  packaged as a structural hypothesis in the same spirit as
  `BrownianMotion.joint_increment_independent`. -/
  joint_past_future_independent :
    ‚ąÄ {s t : ‚ĄĚ}, 0 ‚Č§ s ‚Üí s < t ‚Üí ‚ąÄ {A : Set E}, MeasurableSet A ‚Üí őĹ A ‚Č† ‚ä§ ‚Üí
      ProbabilityTheory.Indep
        (‚®Ü B ‚ąą { C : Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E) | C ‚äÜ Set.Iic s √óňĘ Set.univ ‚ąß MeasurableSet C },
          MeasurableSpace.comap (fun ŌČ => N ŌČ B) inferInstance)
        (MeasurableSpace.comap
          (fun ŌČ => N ŌČ (Set.Ioc s t √óňĘ A)) inferInstance)
        P

/-- The compensated random measure: `√Ď(B) := N(B) ‚ąí őĹŐā(B)` where
`őĹŐā := referenceIntensity őĹ`. Returns a real number when `őĹŐā(B) < ‚ąě`. -/
noncomputable def PoissonRandomMeasure.compensated
    {P : Measure ő©} [IsProbabilityMeasure P]
    {őĹ : Measure E} [SigmaFinite őĹ]
    (N : PoissonRandomMeasure P őĹ) (B : Set (‚ĄĚ √ó E)) (ŌČ : ő©) : ‚ĄĚ :=
  (N.N ŌČ B).toReal - (referenceIntensity őĹ B).toReal

/-- **Step 1: ŌÉ-finite decomposition of the intensity.** A ŌÉ-finite measure `őĹ`
on `E` decomposes as a sequence of pairwise-disjoint measurable sets each of
finite mass covering all of `E`. Built from `MeasureTheory.spanningSets` +
`Set.disjointed`. -/
lemma sigmaFinite_decomposition
    (E : Type v) [MeasurableSpace E] (őĹ : Measure E) [SigmaFinite őĹ] :
    ‚ąÉ s : ‚Ąē ‚Üí Set E,
      (‚ąÄ n, MeasurableSet (s n)) ‚ąß
      Pairwise (fun i j => Disjoint (s i) (s j)) ‚ąß
      (‚ąÄ n, őĹ (s n) < ‚ä§) ‚ąß
      (‚čÉ n, s n) = Set.univ := by
  refine ‚ü®disjointed (MeasureTheory.spanningSets őĹ), ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_‚ü©
  ¬∑ intro n
    exact MeasurableSet.disjointed (MeasureTheory.measurableSet_spanningSets őĹ) n
  ¬∑ exact disjoint_disjointed _
  ¬∑ intro n
    refine lt_of_le_of_lt ?_ (MeasureTheory.measure_spanningSets_lt_top őĹ n)
    exact MeasureTheory.measure_mono (disjointed_subset _ _)
  ¬∑ rw [iUnion_disjointed]
    exact MeasureTheory.iUnion_spanningSets őĹ

/-- **CITED AXIOM: Poisson random measure construction.**

For every ŌÉ-finite intensity `őĹ` on a standard Borel space `E`, there exists a
probability space carrying a Poisson random measure with intensity
`volume.restrict [0,‚ąě) ‚äó őĹ`.

**Reference**: Applebaum, D. *L√©vy Processes and Stochastic Calculus*, 2nd ed.,
Cambridge University Press 2009, Theorem 2.3.1; Kallenberg, O. *Random Measures,
Theory and Applications*, Springer 2017, Proposition 3.6.

**Standard proof outline**: Decompose őĹ as a sum of finite measures (ŌÉ-finiteness);
on each finite piece, construct a finite Poisson random measure via the
"Poisson recipe": (a) sample N ~ Poisson(őĹ(B) ¬∑ vol[0,T]), (b) sample N i.i.d.
points uniformly from B according to őĹ/őĹ(B); take their sum. Use the standard
property that this gives a Poisson random measure. Combine independently across
the ŌÉ-finite decomposition (Mathlib: `MeasureTheory.Measure.pi` + `iIndepFun_pi`).

**Replacement plan**: when Mathlib gains `PoissonRandomMeasure` / `Levy process`
construction, replace this `axiom` with a forwarder. Tracked in
`tools/cited_axioms.md`. -/
axiom PoissonRandomMeasure.exists_of_sigmaFinite
    (E : Type v) [MeasurableSpace E] [StandardBorelSpace E]
    (őĹ : Measure E) [SigmaFinite őĹ] :
    ‚ąÉ (ő© : Type v) (_ : MeasurableSpace ő©) (P : Measure ő©)
      (_ : IsProbabilityMeasure P), Nonempty (PoissonRandomMeasure P őĹ)

/-- **Step 2: Poisson random measure with finite intensity exists.**

Forwarded to the ŌÉ-finite case (`PoissonRandomMeasure.exists_of_sigmaFinite`,
Tier 1 cited axiom #2): any finite measure is automatically ŌÉ-finite (witnessed
by the `[SigmaFinite őĹ]` instance already in the signature), so the ŌÉ-finite
axiom gives the conclusion directly. The `_h_finite : őĹ Set.univ ‚Č† ‚ä§` argument
is retained in the signature for documentation of the original staging plan
(`sigmaFinite_decomposition` ‚Üí finite-piece construction ‚Üí combine), but the
present proof discharges by direct forward ‚ÄĒ the explicit Poisson-recipe
construction outlined in the axiom's docstring is what *would* discharge this
lemma without invoking the ŌÉ-finite axiom; that route is multi-week downstream
work tracked in `tools/cited_axioms.md` #2. -/
lemma poissonRandomMeasure_finite_exists
    (E : Type v) [MeasurableSpace E] [StandardBorelSpace E]
    (őĹ : Measure E) [SigmaFinite őĹ] (_h_finite : őĹ Set.univ ‚Č† ‚ä§) :
    ‚ąÉ (ő© : Type v) (_ : MeasurableSpace ő©) (P : Measure ő©)
      (_ : IsProbabilityMeasure P), Nonempty (PoissonRandomMeasure P őĹ) :=
  PoissonRandomMeasure.exists_of_sigmaFinite E őĹ

